<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> &quot;Humans are not bound completly by nature because we have a choice. That 'choice' throws a wrench into the space and time process.&quot;<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
I think I am missing your point over space-time: I think you are using it an example of raw nature versus &quot;cognized nature&quot; (i.e., nature from an observer's perspective). I believe you are saying that free will of individuals imposes itself on raw nature. Hence, agents with free will are not bound by the laws of nature from a moral point of view. Is that what you are saying? I think another way of looking at this (if I understand you correctly) is that there is a class off sentient beings who create moral laws because they are not bound by their natural condition. I will have to see how you respond before I can say anything over your view of space-time, or how it plays out here.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> &quot;The change came when we Chose to bite the forbidden fruit. The forbiden fruit was not a temptation. It existed because we have free-will. How could we have free-will if everything was not an option.&quot;<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
Just wanted to comment that you make a very nice point above. A very good defenese of why God would provide the fruit to begin with. Of course, it hinges upon whether or not Free Will is an illusion, which I think it is. <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> <br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> &quot;By making that 'choice', we became part of a world where we found ourselves bound by nature, with the exception of the same old guarentee, free-will.&quot;<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
Are you saying that &quot;nature&quot;, in general, has moral qualities? Are apples themselves morally bad? If a Tiger eats a zoo keeper did the Tiger &quot;sin&quot;? Or, are you saying that prior to the eating of the forbidden fruit Tigers didn't eat zoo keepers and apples had no moral disposition? And why do you think free will was exempt from this decline to nature?<br>
<br>
What is intersting to me is the ancient dichotomy of &quot;good&quot; vs. &quot;Evil&quot;. Why maintain such a view? The world without social laws is neither good or evil.<br>
<br>
Also, I find it funny that God could create beings with free will, knowledge, and have them live in a paradise and his only answer to their choice to have knowledge is to take away paradise and remove the sinners from his presence?! I would say that god is not very creative at all. Seems like their should have been a better solution. But I am off topic now. <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> <br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> &quot;So now humakind is still trying to understand 'life'. In all ways. Eventually, the path will lead us back to truth and love.&quot;<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
Hold on... I thought eating of the forbidden fruit would give us an understanding of life? Weren't we supposed to get knowledge of good and evil? Was the fruit a placebo?<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> &quot;God, just like any loving mother or father, chose to create a world, or environment condusive for love ad truth. But since we wanted to try it all for ourselves, we got it.&quot;<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
Um, when my Children want to &quot;try it all&quot; for themselves (called adulthood) I am not going to kick them out of my house. I certainly will not punish them for wanting knowledge and trying to obtain it.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> &quot;But I don't believe anyone person has the ability to learn everything of the consequences of his actions.&quot;<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
Now we get to the meat of the matter! <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->  I don't think it is a requirement to learn all the consequences of an action in order to understand that the effects of some actions are not desirable. I don't have to shoot up heroin to understand its effects will be bad for me. We really do comprehend the results of our actions when presented to us. If we can't &quot;comprehend&quot; the results we haven't learned anything at all from our actions; hence &quot;history repeats itself&quot; for some. This is really the crux of the issue I have presented, Brutas. I am not trying to be disrespectful when I say Christians are morally weak. They are weak precisely because they never fully actualize the pain and pleasure associated with their behaviors. Should a Christian sin they quickly retreat to blaming their &quot;fallen natures&quot; and repent to Jesus for being such miserable sinners. If they do good deeds it is the grace of God that allows them to do good. In either case, the Christian never gets to deal with themselves. They never get to take credit; hence life for them is one long state of moral bereaving. Why would a god want to create such a dependancy? Why wouldn't he want his creation to take full credit and full responsibility for their actions? I will tell you, it is the god of those who created him in order to keep the masses weak and dependent. It is the Popes of the world who are responsible, it keeps them in power.<br>
<br>
This posting is very long as it is... I will leave it here. Looking forward to your response. <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> <br>
